<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38214c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38214c">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38214c"> 214(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> mass mo<font color="green">[v]</font>ings</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">That is <mark>the mass movement</mark> &mdash; a tiny fragment of it. Multiply the picture by a hundred, or perhaps a thousand time and you will have some conception of that movement <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> A mass movement is (obviously) a movement of people <i>en masse</i> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Then it suggests the idea of a people <mark>moving</mark> in obedience to some instinct or for the achievement of some purpose, or both combined <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> In its religious or missionary connotation a mass movement is the simultaneous and (more or less) concerted acceptance of Christianity by a whole people, usually in groups or companies here and there, and their baptism in groups, such group baptisms occurring with the comparative frequency until the whole, or a large proportion, of the people have become Christian. <small> Rev W.S. Hunt, <a name="WSHI" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WSHI"><cite title="source">India's Outcastes: A New Era</cite></a> (1924) 3-4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The Church Missionary Society mission in India began early in the early years of the Society&apos;s existence, in the early nineteenth century; the period Hunt describes is from the mid-nineteenth century to the 1920s.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c08041c" href="c8all.htm#c08041c">VI.C.08:041(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
